rComments: very bad teaching skills, and bad writing. his ppt can make people very sleepy but he requires attendance. if you not attending his zoom meeting more than 20% of the class, he will fail you. tests are hard on each question but still solvable, but very hard.

Good prof, great at explaining the material. He is very organized and provides different formats for the slides including formula sheets, which I find very helpful for studying. Encourages questions/participation and is available to help if something isn't clear. Would recommend!

Professor Zarepour is a good professor and he's accessible outside of class hours. However, he only marks the hardest questions on the assignments which is not fair. Exams are similar to the content covered in class, but they're too long so make sure you're 100% ready for them.

Very understandable professor. Wants you to do well and take the most from class. Sometimes not the most clear and this means that usually each assignment will seem "impossible" at first. However, after asking for clarification or emailing him, you will understand the questions very well. Midterm and Final were manageable.
Sometimes his explanations can be a bit confusing, but on the whole he really wants to make sure you understand the material. Lecture slides are good as well.

Pros: you truly learn the foundation of probability; thorough lecture slides; he really wants you to learn Cons: tough grader, don't try to get extra marks (it doesn't work lol) Comments: you gotta actually do the work and study, attend class and office hours as needed to pass.

Zarepour is really irritated by just about everything. Very smart guy, but goes very fast and makes things hard to understand. His examples are good but the theory is hard to follow.
just go to class, listen and take good notes. Then ask questions during office hours or after class. You need to do the work and he will help you get there.
I am taking the course now and I am learning a lot. Doing more questions outside of class actually helps me (i.e. important to do the homework)

provides good examples in class, also assignments are good indicator of exam difficulty. He is a good prof, I wouldn't skip his class especially before midterm and final exams because he gives lot's of hints about the type of question that might be asked. Overall, fair exams , if you work hard through the assignments, It's easy to get A++

Really encouraging

Good prof. There is a bit of a language barrier, but nothing too bad. You definitely need to go to class to do well though - he doesn't follow the textbook and likes to use his own notation. He yelled at our class a lot. He's decent at explaining things in class but the difficulty of exams is just brutal.

assignments are a fairly clear indication of the level of difficulty of his upcoming exams (Midterm and final). I also did some extra practice Qs from the textbook and it helped my understanding.

A Good Prof, Midterm and exam were open book, which helped if you went to every class and took good notes, do the assignments and go see him if you have a problem right away dont wait. Overall a good prof who does a lot of examples in class and wants you to learn the material.

You need help, just go to his office hours! Thats all I should say, really!!  Dr. Zarepour forces me to think hard and critically about a question. I really appreciate that. I've learned a lot from him.

You learn a lot from him. They way he teaches , you'll never forget. If you want to succeed in his course, don't miss classes and read his notes. He actually wants you to learn and I don't find him rude at all. He was always there when I had a question and I'm 100% satisfied with my grade.

Dr. Zarepour is an excellent professor. He is absolutely skilled in Mathematics and Statistics. You can see how much he loves the subject. He is very approachable. He took 45 minutes to explain an assignment to me. I highly recommend taking any class with him. He might come off rude or assertive but he really isn't. Don't be shy to ask.

N.B. He does NOT teach SYS5120. He only teaches stats. In his class, there is such a thing as a stupid question. And he talks a good game, but details are often wrong. He knows little about stats in the real world.
